          "title": "Ethical Decision-Making Frameworks",
          "content": "When you find yourself facing an ethical decision, it can be really helpful to follow a structured framework that guides you through the process. This framework consists of six important steps that can help you make thoughtful and responsible choices.\nFirst, the very first step is to clearly identify the ethical issue at hand. This means taking the time to understand what the problem is and why it matters. It’s crucial to recognize the significance of the issue you are dealing with.\nNext, the second step involves gathering all relevant facts. This means collecting all the information you need to make a well-informed decision. The more facts you have, the better your understanding of the situation will be.\nThe third step is to identify all stakeholders who might be affected by your decision. Stakeholders can include a variety of people such as employees, customers, and even members of the community. Understanding who will be impacted helps you consider different perspectives.\nIn the fourth step, you will evaluate your options by looking at them through different ethical lenses. This includes considering the utilitarian perspective, which focuses on achieving the greatest good for the greatest number of people. You should also think about the deontological perspective, which emphasizes following rules and duties. Additionally, consider the virtue-based perspective, which focuses on the character traits you want to embody, and the rights-based perspective, which looks at the individual rights of those involved.\nThe fifth step is to make your decision and then test it. A good way to test your decision is to ask yourself if you would feel comfortable if your reasoning was published in a newspaper. This helps ensure that your decision aligns with your values and ethics.\nFinally, the sixth step is to implement your decision. After putting your decision into action, it’s important to monitor the outcomes and reflect on what you learned from the experience. This reflection can help you grow and improve your decision-making skills in the future. By following this structured approach, you can make sure that your decisions are made thoughtfully and ethically, which is essential in any business context.\nContext recap: When you find yourself facing an ethical decision, it can be really helpful to follow a structured framework that guides you through the process. This framework consists of six important steps that can help you make thoughtful and responsible choices. First, the very first step is to clearly identify the ethical issue at hand. This means taking the time to understand what the problem is and why it matters.\nWhy this matters: Ethical Decision-Making Frameworks helps learners in Business connect ideas from Business Ethics Foundations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
